unit.name: 26 Infantry Division HQ
unit.History: The 26th Division was reactivated in January 1941. Under the command of Major General Paul it landed at Cherbourg and Omaha Beach in early September 1944. The 26th entered combat a month later in Lorraine as part of the Third Army's XIX Corps. It had seen considerable combat during the XIX Corps Seille-Saar campaign (8 November through 8 December), and was resting as part of the III Corps in Third Army reserve when the Germans opened their offensive in the Ardennes.

commander.Name: Willard S. Paul
commander.PersBio: Willard S. Paul (1894-1966) was a native of Massachusetts. He served in the Colorado National Guard and was commissioned a lieutenant in the regular army at the start of World War I. After the war he served as Assistant Chief of Staff (G-1) and retired from the army in December 1948 as a Lieutenant General. Following his retirement he was a consultant to the American National Red Cross (1948-1950), an assistant to Director of Defense Mobilization Arthur S. Flemming (1954-56), and a member of a special Subcommittee of the Hoover Commission which studied personnel problems of the Defense Department (1955-56). In 1956 he became president of Gettysburg College in Pennsylvania, from which he retired in 1961.

commander.Name: Lt. Col. James Rosborugh
commander.PersBio: Carear FA officer from Pennslyvania, known to his troops as "Jungle Jim". Was universally admired by his troops as shining example of selflessness and bravery no matter how serious the situation. Was awarded the DSC for his actions in the defense of his battalion and in support of the 109th.
